<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC's crime and punishment season continues tonight with an absorbing
Assignment (BBC2, 7.45pm), examining the Japanese way of crime - low rates,
good prisons, but rather nasty prying police plus new ruthless types of
gangsters on the way.
Two excellent nature programmes worth making an effort to see - In Praise of
Penguins (Channel 4, 4pm), splendidly narrated by Richard Briers, and
Wildlife 100 (BBC1, 7pm), on ants in Panama and the Amazon jungle, with
David Attenborough.
Testimonies (Channel 4, 9pm) holds a mirror up to the Israeli army's
behaviour in its combat against Palestinians involved in the six-year old
Intifada. Some may feel its critique of Israeli army violence fails to
address some basic political questions - like, it takes two to be peaceful.
ITV has given up all pretence of scheduling intelligent programmes until
bedtime. Disappearing World (ITV, 10.40pm), one of the last quality
controlled ITV programmes, tonight features the 50 year old bloody civil war
of the Karen tribesmen against Burma's military bullyboys.
</TEXT>
