<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Smith might offer deal on block
vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN SMITH, the Labour leader, yesterday took his campaign for
one-member-one-vote and an end to the union block vote in the election of
the party's parliamentary candidates to the MSF general technical union.
There are signs that Mr Smith will have to compromise with the unions to
avoid a split over the issue at this autumn's party conference.
He told delegates to the MSF's conference in Blackpool he wanted to offer
trade unionists who pay the political levy a special lower party membership
rate to encourage them to become 'full participating members' in Labour
constituency parties.
But Mr John Edmonds, general secretary of the GMB general union said last
night that although this was 'a first step in the right direction', it 'did
not address the problem of what to do about political levy payers in the
unions'.
He said they should be entitled to a direct say in the selection of Labour
candidates.
At present the larger unions including the TGWU transport workers' union and
the GMB want to retain a link through their political levy payers in
candidate selection.
Their view looks likely to prevail among the unions that will account for 70
per cent of the vote at party conference. The MSF will debate the issue
tomorrow.
In the past few weeks the Usdaw shopworkers' union conference voted narrowly
against the idea and the NCU communication workers' union also looks likely
to reject it.
</TEXT>
