<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Inner-city funds contest may reopen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL HOWARD, the environment secretary, yesterday held out the
prospect of a further round of City Challenge, the government programme
which invites local authorities to bid for funds for inner city
regeneration.
Opening the Cities '93 conference in Birmingham, Mr Howard said a further
round would depend on the results of an assessment of the first two rounds
of City Challenge, in which 31 of the 57 urban priority areas each won
Pounds 75m a year over five years for regeneration.
No further money is available for City Challenge in this year's public
spending plans. But funds will be available in 1994-95 as three-year urban
programme projects come to an end.
Mr Howard said about half of the government's Pounds 4bn budget for urban
develop-ment was already allocated through competitive bid-ding.
He was looking at ways of increasing competition among local authorities for
his department's funds.
'If money is handed out as a matter of routine and accepted as a matter of
routine, it will be spent as a matter or routine,' he said. 'Competition
provides an escape from the dead hand of routine.'
Even areas which were unsuccessful in City Challenge find that the process
of bidding sparked the imagination and energy of local people and
businesses, he said.
'Far more is achieved than before, and lasting relationships are formed.'
</TEXT>
