<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: More franchises for BR sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday signalled its determination to proceed with the
privatisation of British Rail by setting out its detailed plans for
transferring the whole of the passenger network to the private sector.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, announced that BR's passenger
services would be divided into 25 geographically based business units which
would ultimately be taken over by private sector franchisees.
Mr MacGregor predicted that the first franchises would be handed over to the
private sector in the second half of next year and that a 'substantial
proportion' of passenger services would be in private hands within the
lifetime of the current parliament.
However, he said it was impossible to predict how long the process would
take to complete.
Mr MacGregor said he placed particular importance on the fact that
franchising would be an 'evolutionary' process. 'There won't be sudden
dramatic difficulties in terms of big closures or anything like that,' he
said.
'As people see their services improving, as people start to see the
individual franchises working, they will start to see the whole point of
it.'
The 25 franchise areas - which include seven announced in February - will be
operated by BR as 'shadow' franchises until they pass to the private sector.
The aim is that they build up a trading record that will be known when the
bidding begins.
Mr MacGregor said the precise boundaries of the franchise areas could change
if that helped the pro-cess.
The Department of Transport has also yet to settle on a final scheme for
franchising Regional Railways' sprawling central division, the Regional
Railways long-distance services and InterCity's cross-country operations.
Mr MacGregor confirmed that overseas railways such as SNCF, the French
national railway, would not be precluded from bidding, but said the
franchising director would be looking for bidders with a commercial
orientation.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
