<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 93 / Cinema audiences increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CINEMA is making a strong comeback in the UK with audiences higher last
year than in any year since 1980, the latest Cultural Trends report shows.
More than 60 per cent of the population aged 7 and older goes to the cinema
and more than 30 per cent of the 15-24 age group does so once a month or
more. The estimated total audience last year was 101m.
Cinema box-office takings, at under Pounds 300m, account for little more
than a fifth of the Pounds 1.4bn total consumer expenditure on films. The
balance comes from expenditure such as video hire and subscriptions to
television film channels.
Radio is the other expanding media sector highlighted in the report compiled
from available statistics and published today by the Policy Studies
Institute, an independent research organisation.
Helped by the launch of Classic FM, radio attracted 41.6m listeners a week -
89 per cent of the population - during the last quarter of 1992. BBC Radio,
which had a record budget of Pounds 338.2m in 1991-92, is gradually losing
audience share to its commercial rivals, but still has more than 58 per cent
of the market.
Mr Jeremy Eckstein, editor of Cultural Trends, believes the picture in the
television market is one of remarkable stability. 'The whole thing is
operating within a fully saturated market,' he said. 'There have been
enormous changes in production, but so far as viewers are concerned there is
no change at all.'
Overall the impact of cable and satellite television was still very modest,
accounting for around 5 per cent of total viewing and 30 per cent in cable
and satellite homes. The recession is blamed for slowing cable and satellite
growth.
Cultural Trends 17. Policy Studies Institute Pounds 15.50. From bookshops or
from BEBC, PO Box 1496, Poole, Dorset BH12 3YD.
</TEXT>
