<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 93 / Education voucher scheme proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT may introduce a common credit for the education and training
of 16 to 19-year-olds, Mrs Gillian Shephard, the employment secretary,
hinted yesterday.
She told senior managers the move would be a 'step we might consider in
opening up a real market in training and education.' The government is
understood to be considering publishing a white paper on the issue.
The option of a common system of funding for academic, vocational and job
specific training, first proposed by the Confederation of British Industry,
was endorsed in a ministerial review of the education and training of 16 to
19-year-olds conducted by the education and employment departments. The CBI
has developed its idea into what it calls Careership, under which all
16-year-olds would receive a voucher or financial credit which they could
exchange for training or education. The CBI says this would enable people to
shop around for the best opportunities, and open up competition among
providers.
Three years ago, the government set up pilots of a more limited scheme -
involving young people undertaking vocational training - which is due to be
extended nationally in 1996. Take-up in pilot areas has been uneven. Mrs
Shephard said yesterday: 'What the CBI is saying is that we should look to
market mechanisms to express choices and achieve value for money.'
The size of classes at state-maintained nursery schools in England rose last
year, education department figures showed yesterday. There were 25 pupils
for every teacher last year compared with 24.2 in 1991 and 23 in 1983. If
nursery assistants are taken into account, the ratio last year was 11
children for every staff member, which was similar to 1991. The figure in
1983 was 10.4.
</TEXT>
