<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 93 / Curriculum for technology rapped: National Institute attacks
'demotivating' syllabus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NATIONAL curriculum for technology in England and Wales has led to
'great difficulties in teaching' and leaves less academic children
'disadvantaged and demotivated', the National Institute for Economic and
Social Research says.
It adds that the quality of practical learning opportunities is below that
in Germany, the Netherlands and Switzerland.
The institute article, written by Helvia Bierhoff and Sigmund Prais,
criticises technology teaching in the last two years of compulsory schooling
for being too intellectualised, and for requiring pupils to work in a broad
range of materials. They say national curriculum requirements 'have led to
inadequate specialisation, inadequate progression, and to poor quality of
finished work'.
They also criticise the attitude adopted in English and Welsh schools,
saying: 'Unless practical subjects are intellectualised and linked to
academic subjects and bulky paperwork activities, they continue to be
regarded as not having a wholly legitimate place in the school curriculum.'
New proposals for the national curriculum published late last year would
encourage higher-quality work by allowing greater specialisation and more
practical work, the report says. But it suggests schools are not equipped
with the specialised workshops teachers need to take advantage of the
proposals.
The report criticises attainment targets set by the national curriculum,
including a requirement for pupils to 'identify needs and opportunities' for
technology in different contexts.
The aim is to free pupils from the 'straitjacket' of doing what the teacher
told them, but the institute found some national curriculum targets to be
irrelevant to pupils' everyday lives.
The institute's authors prefer the Continental approach of concentrating on
practical subjects.
They found that Continental schools allowed a third (or more) of their
pupils between the ages of 14 and 16 to do systematic courses in specialised
disciplines such as woodwork, metalwork and textiles. Continental employers
believed that pupils taught this way were more motivated, had better work
habits, and learned how to respond responsibly to instructions in applied
contexts.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9411 Administration of Educational Programs.
    P8211 Elementary and Secondary Schools.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
