<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 93 / Challenge on power prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TWO main electricity generators for England and Wales were warned by the
industry regulator yesterday that they might face a monopolies referral if
they failed to explain adequately why their prices have risen since March.
Professor Stephen Littlechild, director-general of the Office of Electricity
Regulation (Offer), also said he was investigating complaints about the
attitude of National Power, the main generator, to potential buyers of plant
it plans to close.
The two issues are among several potential areas of conflict between the
regulator and the generators. Prof Littlechild, who is also investigating
the generators' costs and margins, has said he will decide on a referral to
the Monopolies and Mergers Commission by 1995.
'Perhaps the decision will have to be taken earlier,' he said yesterday.
A growing number of analysts believe a referral is inevitable, although some
believe the regulator would be unwilling to let the future of the industry
be decided by authorities outside his control. Prof Littlechild, publishing
his annual report yesterday, said improvements in the industry since
privatisation included a sharp reduction in domestic disconnections - down
62 per cent 1991 and 1992 - and the growth of electricity supply
competition.
The main area of difficulty was the market power of National Power and
PowerGen, the two main generators, he said, even though competition was
increasing through the expansion of independent power plants.
He said he had received little response from the generators following his
request three weeks ago for an explanation of price rises in the electricity
wholesale pool this month and in April. 'I am treating this as a serious
matter,' he said. 'It is extremely important that pool works efficiently.'
Although he has also asked National Grid for an explanation of why
pool-associated prices have risen, he said that company's role was not a
cause for concern.
Prof Littlechild also said he believed there was scope for development in
the way the pool operated. Because prices were determined only by bids from
the generators of electricity it was only 'half a market'. He said
demand-side bidding, under which large users could be paid to reduce demand
at short notice, could lead to more stability and efficiency. Prof
Littlechild said he hoped to complete a review of price controls of the
regional electricity companies' supply businesses by the end of June.
Offer Annual Report 1992. HMSO, Pounds 12.50.
