<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 93 / Rowland assaults biography with fax barrage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR TINY ROWLAND, joint chief executive of Lonrho, and his wife Josie last
night issued statements criticising an unauthorised biography, A Rebel
Tycoon. The book is by Mr Tom Bower, whose last book was The Outsider, an
acclaimed account of the life of Robert Maxwell.
Mr Rowland dealt yesterday with his unsolicited biography in just three
sentences. 'I very much regret that a boring and unrecognisable account of
my life should have been published today,' he said in a faxed statement to
the media. 'None of the interesting bits are in. I know many people, but,
thank God, not the author.'
Mr Bower laughed last night when told of the Lonrho chief's statement and
added: 'It's his way of trying to minimise something that he would have
preferred hadn't happened.' Mr Rowland's fax was followed by a more
threatening one from Mrs Josie Rowland. 'Apart from the fact that I love my
husband every other reference to me is untrue and denigratory,' it said. She
was demanding an apology from Mr Bower and publishers Heinemann within 48
hours or she would issue writs. Mr Rowland's statement did not threaten
legal action.
To avoid the possibility of an injunction to prevent publication the book
was printed in Finland and copies were brought into the UK and distributed
only last Thursday.
The book makes serious allegations about how Lonrho is run and behaves in
Africa.
In Sunday's Observer, Mr Rowland published an account of his life and also
swiped at Mr Bower.
'My life has been my own, and I feel that it's copyright,' he wrote. 'A man
I have never met or spoken to, to my knowledge, is going to exhibit me for
commercial gain on his part, smearing and distorting everything that belongs
to me and giving me a character of his own choosing.'
Mr Bower said last night there was nothing new in the 'rather fanciful'
Observer account, 'except I didn't know he was so high up in the Hitler
youth.' Mr Rowland wrote in the Observer that he had reached the rank of
troop leader in charge of 150 boys.
</TEXT>
