<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 93 / 'Failures' admitted by ECGD
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EXPORT Credits Guarantee Department, the government-owned export credit
agency, yesterday admitted that it had failed to observe Treasury rules,
failed to report fraud and failed to keep records in a transaction in which
it lost Pounds 41.4m.
The loss was disclosed in the ECGD's most recent accounts, which reveal the
department's involvement with a Mexican oil rig operator which left it the
owner of two rigs.
Details of the ECGD's handling of the affair emerged yesterday when Mr Brian
Willott, head of the department since January 1992, gave evidence to the
Commons public accounts committee.
He said the affair was a 'built-in disaster'. Admitting to the 'very large
number of serious management failures' listed by Mr Robert Sheldon,
committee chairman, Mr Willott insisted that the ECGD had taken steps to
tighten its claims and underwriting procedures: 'The lessons of this case
are branded rather deep in the collective conscience of the ECGD.'
The affair dated back to 1980, when the ECGD insured loans totalling Dollars
53.5m for the Mexican company Perforaciones Maritimas del Golfo (Permago) to
buy two oil rigs built by the Marathon yards in Scotland.
In 1982, almost immediately after delivery, drilling contracts for the rigs
were cancelled and the company defaulted on loan repay-ments.
Over the next 10 years, the ECGD opted to refinance the company rather than
press for sale of the rigs; discovered two frauds linked with Permago, which
it did not report to the government's Fraud Investigation Branch; failed to
keep records of meetings about the case; and provided overdraft facilities
in contravention of Treasury rules.
It made the refinancing decision without seeking advice on prospective oil
price movements - critical to the likely profitability of the rigs.
It failed to have departmental lawyers present in negotiations with Permago.
The case was not referred above the ECGD's claims department until late
stages. Mr Willott did not even pay 'serious attention' to the case until
July 1992, six months after assuming office, he told the committee.
In February this year the ECGD repossessed the rigs, but not before a lack
of main-tenance resulted in repair costs rising from Dollars 500,000 to
Dollars 5m.
It is now trying to sell the rigs, and hopes to recoup between Pounds 12m
and Pounds 20m - leaving taxpayers to carry a net loss of Pounds 20m to
Pounds 30m.
Mr Willott admitted that for most of the period concerned, the ECGD had
failed to consult with other government departments, since 'it tended to
regard itself as having the sole expertise in this area. We are now less
reluctant to consult others'.
He said no one in the department had been punished, but said all concerned
had retired.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
