<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 93 / Pipeline may supply gas to Belgium
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR TIM EGGAR, energy minister, is expected to announce in the Commons today
the publication of a prospectus for the Pounds 300m gas pipe project between
the UK and the Continent.
A group of companies including British Gas, British Petroleum and Norway's
Statoil have been involved in an initial feasibility study which could
involve the export of UK gas to continental Europe.
Mr Eggar will refer to the prospectus in a parliamentary answer. It should
set out details of the so-called Europipe venture in an effort to gauge the
amount of interest among energy companies for the private-sector project.
A steering committee of seven companies involved in the initial technical
studies is considering a plan to build a pipeline between Bacton, in
Norfolk, and Zeebrugge in Belgium, with export capacity of 15bn cu m a year,
or a third of current UK output.
However, companies are not sure of the commercial viability of such a
scheme. Statoil said yesterday it had not yet decided whether to participate
in the project.
Mr Eggar is understood to have told the companies involved that the UK
government is ready to negotiate a treaty with the Belgian authorities about
the proposed Europipe linking up with the Belgian national grid.
The government is keen for the Europipe project to go ahead and is linking
the success of the venture to a decision to allow additional supplies of
Norwegian gas to flow into the UK. But there has been some scepticism about
the viability of the planned project because it is unlikely the gas could
compete with lower-cost supplies from Russia.
Other companies involved in the plan include Norsk Hydro, the Norwegian
resources group, Elf Aquitaine, France's energy group, Conoco UK and
Distrigaz of Belgium.
