<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 93 / Milan magistrates open another significant line of enquiry
into corruption
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Milan magistrates have opened another significant line of enquiry into
corruption in the form of political kick-backs on contracts controlled by
the Culture Ministry, Robert Graham reports from Rome. Yesterday, police
arrested Mr Alberto Ciampaglia, former treasurer of the small Social
Democrat party, for allegedly receiving a L400m (Pounds 175,510) payment
from an architect for restoration work. Last week Ms Vincenza Bono Parrino,
Social Democrat culture minister from 1988 to 1989, was warned she was under
investigation for allegedly receiving L2.5bn for restoration contracts for
historic monuments.
Mr Ciampaglia was one of four people arrested yesterday in connection with
the culture ministry enquiry. In another development, Mr Francesco Forte, a
prominent Socialist senator and former finance minister, announced he had
received notice that he was under investigation for allegedly receiving
illicit funds.
