<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 93 / Spanish Elections: Gonzalez faces another scandal over party
funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SPAIN'S ruling Socialist party yesterday moved a step closer to defeat in
the June 6 election after a Madrid newspaper published allegations that the
party may have illegally financed the 1986 referendum campaign to remain in
Nato.
The Socialists, while not denying the charges, said they were a political
attack. The income was not illegal, the party said, since it pre-dated the
current party financing law. The allegations, published so close to the
election, are bound to affect wavering voters. The conservative Partido
Popular and the Socialists continue to run neck-and-neck. Although the
Socialists appear to have escaped from the recent peseta devaluation and
increase in unemployment with little damage, a new corruption scandal could
be much more wounding.
Polls suggest that up to half the electorate is undecided, and many former
Socialist voters have been dismayed by the torrent of corruption charges
made against the party in the last four years. El Mundo, the newspaper which
published the charges, alleged the party raised more than Pounds 3.2m in
1986, mainly in the form of commissions paid to it by construction
companies. El Mundo has been responsible for uncovering nearly all the
scandals that have weakened the prime minister, Mr Felipe Gonzalez,
including the so-called Filesa scandal, which is credited with having forced
Mr Gonzalez to call an early election.
Filesa was a dummy consultancy company run by Socialist party officials,
which raised more than Pounds 6.4m in the late 1980s by selling reports and
services to client companies. None of the reports has ever been produced and
Treasury inspectors suspect they do not exist. The Filesa cash is alleged to
have been used to finance the Socialists' 1989 election campaign.
The new El Mundo claims came just before Mr Gonzalez held a televised
election debate with his main political challenger, the Partido Popular
leader, Mr Jose Mara Aznar.
Up to 5m people watched a dull late-night debate in which Mr Gonzalez
unexpectedly failed to dent his increasingly confident opponent. Often on
the defensive, the prime minister failed to force Mr Aznar to speak in any
detail about the Partido Popular's economic plans, which remain the
campaign's best kept secret.
Editorial Comment, Page 21
</TEXT>
