<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 93 / EC draws up jobs strategy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Community could begin to roll back unemployment by such
measures as reducing employers' social security contributions to cut labour
costs and more sharing-out of jobs. This is the main conclusion of the
'Community-wide framework for employment' the European Commission is set to
adopt tomorrow.
The framework policy, approved in its essentials yesterday by the chefs de
cabinet of the Commission, puts forward a jobs-crisis agenda for the next
three presidencies of the EC, to the end of 1994.
It starts from the premise that a return to the high economic and
productivity growth of the late 1980s 'would still leave the Community well
short of a target such as 5 per cent unemployment'. The EC now has 17.4m
jobless, 10.3 per cent of the workforce.
But the Commission confidently says 'there is sufficient evidence and
experience to suggest that ways of, at least, improving the situation can be
found - over and above those which can result from higher levels of economic
growth.'
The proposed strategy, likely to be near the top of the agenda at next
month's Copenhagen summit of EC heads of government, is the first EC-wide
attempt to deal with structural unemployment. It focuses on ways of creating
more labour-intensive growth.
The document notes that while Belgium and the Netherlands have similar
labour productivity, the Dutch provide jobs for 10 per cent more people of
working age. The Danes earn less per head in real terms than western
Germans, but have a much higher portion of their people at work.
'You can have labour-intensive work while still providing a highly
competitive product,' said one senior Brussels official. 'It's a question of
how you share a given volume of employment between people.'
The Commission is at pains to stress that its strategy is consonant with the
'economic and social aims' of EC member states. It would 'not exploit
workers in a weak position in the labour market, or inhibit the development
of the high value-added, knowledge-based jobs which will be the key to
future competitiveness.'
But it suggests employers' 'social contributions' - averaging 15 per cent of
wages across the EC but varying between member states from virtually nil to
over 20 per cent - affect job creation. The five main points of its
framework therefore call for: 'reducing labour costs. . . notably by
modifying the incidence of taxation systems'; new working time structures to
share out jobs; 'adaptability at the workplace' and 'new forms of work
organisation'; training systems to bring more people into work and
'anticipate structural change'; and exploitation of 'new areas of work' such
as the environment.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9441 Administration of Social and Manpower Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
