<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 93 / Ministers consider flotation to fund tunnel rail link
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is considering a plan to fund the Pounds 2.5bn rail link
between London and the Channel tunnel by inviting the public to buy shares
in the project through a stock market flotation.
The plan could end the long delay in starting the project by overcoming the
government's difficulties in raising the finance necessary for construction.
Last week the delay led to diplomatic embarrassment when President Francois
Mitterrand of France marked the opening of a high-speed rail link on the
French side of the Channel tunnel by deriding the lack of progress on the
British side.
If the plan goes ahead, the most likely timing of the flotation will be
around September 1995 - after the government has obtained the necessary
legislation, but before construction work begins.
This means private sector investors will run the risk of seeing their
returns diminished by unexpected increases in construction costs, so
bringing comparisons with Eurotunnel, the Channel tunnel concessionaire,
which was floated on the stock market in 1987.
The government's advisers are likely to claim, however, that lessons have
been learned from the cost runs that have hit Eurotunnel, and that the
construction risks involved in building a railway are in any case far fewer.
The flotation plan emerged yesterday as the Department of Transport opened
discussions with the private sector about ways of involving private capital
in building the link.
The project cannot be funded entirely by the private sector because it is
not sufficiently profitable.
The department has therefore sent out a consultation paper to banks,
construction companies and other institutions looking atthe options for
funding the project jointly. One option explored in the paper is that the
government could say what contribution it was prepared to make and then let
private sector companies compete to take the project over at an early stage
of the planning process, towards the end of this year.
But an alternative plan explored in the paper is for the public sector to
hold on to the project through the design and legislative phases until
construction is ready to begin in September 1995, and then float the project
on the stock market with a government grant big enough to turn it into
profit.
A possible vehicle for the flotation would be Union Railways, the British
Rail subsidiary in charge of the project.
More franchises for BR sell-off, Page 13
</TEXT>
<XX>
