<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 93 / Abu Dhabi close to charges over BCCI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT of Abu Dhabi is close to bringing both civil and criminal
actions against the key individuals from the collapsed Bank of Credit and
Commerce International who it believes defrauded it of Dollars 2.2bn (Pounds
1.42bn).
The government, which is the majority shareholder in the bank, is at an
advanced stage of determining whether to sue for compensation former BCCI
directors and employees it alleges stole money it entrusted to the bank
through ICIC, a Cayman Islands subsidiary.
The money came from the private departments of Sheikh Zayed, the ruler of
Abu Dhabi, and Sheikh Khalifa, the crown prince. These men, along with the
state department of finance and Adia, the state investment authority, hold
77 per cent of BCCI's shares.
The public prosecutor's office is believed to be near bringing criminal
charges against 13 individuals detained in the country since BCCI was closed
in July 1991, including Mr Swaleh Naqvi, its former chief executive.
The action comes as the liquidators to the bank at accountants Touche Ross
are believed to be close to making a decision on whether to issue writs
against the Bank of England for its role as lead regulator to BCCI. The
liquidators have already issued writs for damages of more than Dollars 8bn
against accountants Price Waterhouse and Ernst &amp; Whinney, now part of Ernst
&amp; Young, for their role as auditors to the bank, and of Dollars 10.5bn
against the National Commercial Bank of Saudi Arabia and Sheikh Khalid bin
Mahfouz, its former chief operating officer, for fraud and racketeering.
The government of Abu Dhabi would itself sue the individual BCCI employees,
while all other litigation is being handled by Touche Ross. Any proceeds
will be split equally between the two parties.
The prospect of new litigation comes as Touche Ross prepares for the
election of a formal five-strong creditors' committee from 24 candidates
this Thursday, at what is expected to be the world's largest creditors'
meeting at London's Wembley arena. The committee will approve the firm's
fees and sanction its future actions.
Adia, the Abu Dhabi investment authority, which is owed at least Dollars
72m, has put up a candidate. Also standing is Mr Adil Elias, owed Dollars
2m, who is a member of the existing informal creditors' committee and who is
opposing in the Luxembourg courts the settlement between Abu Dhabi and
Touche Ross.
BCCI victims gather, Page 10
</TEXT>
