<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 93 / Government to consider safeguards for cheap BR fares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT last night hinted it might agree legal safeguards for
concessionary rail fares in order to avoid a Commons defeat at the hands of
Conservative backbench rebels.
With the British Rail privatisation bill returning to the House of Commons
today for its report stage, Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, said he
was willing to look at possible statutory protection for railcards.
But Mr MacGregor indicated the government would not yield to a separate
demand by some Tory MPs that BR be allowed to compete for service franchises
once the railways are thrown open to private competition.
The two-day debate on the bill's report stage threatens to be stormy with
concern among the government's supporters about the political impact of
privatisation underpinned by evidence of overwhelming public opposition.
Mr John Prescott, Labour's transport spokesman, pledged the opposition to
return the rail network to the public sector if it won the next general
election.
A Gallup poll last week suggested that more than two-thirds of commuters
opposed the privatisation of services. Yesterday a report commissioned by
the public transport pressure group Transport 2000 said fares would have to
increase sharply and rural services shut to meet a Pounds 500m 'bill' for
privatisation.
Legal guarantees for the concessionary fares enjoyed by the elderly and
students have been demanded by about a dozen Conservative backbenchers,
threatening the government's 18-seat majority in the Commons.
Mr MacGregor had suggested that they could be protected in agreements
reached between the new franchise authority and private sector operators.
But Sir Keith Speed, the MP for Ashford who is leading Tory calls for
tighter safeguards, said that the government risked defeat unless it was
prepared to enshrine the principle of concessionary fares in the
legislation.
That brought a statement from Mr MacGregor: 'If we can find a way of meeting
some of the concerns obviously I will do so because . . . I am well aware of
the importance of railcards.' The Tory rebels now expect the government to
table its own amendment to protect the cheap fares.
Mr MacGregor refused to offer a comparable olive branch to the rebels on
their demands that BR should be able to compete equally with private sector
companies in bidding for franchises.
Editorial Comment, Page 15
</TEXT>
