<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
What would we do without BBC2? It is beginning to look like the last bastion
of intelligent programming.
Tonight it continues the Crime and Punishment short season with two
likely-looking offerings. Horizon (BBC2, 8pm) is subtitled 'Wot U Looking
At?', that popular greeting familiar from almost all venues featuring
contact sports, pop music and Oxbridge May balls.
It's a stitch-up (BBC2, 9pm) is an inventive attempt to bring the arcane
obscurities of the judicial system into closer focus, by turning it into a
game show. But everything that happens to the hapless defendant is quite
accurate and rather unfunny.
But for bad taste, tonight's Singles (ITV, 10.40pm) is unbeatable. The
unwitting buffoon of this edition is Nick, who believes that dressing up as
a bear will help him find true love - or at least quick sex. Compellingly
awful and genuinely more damaging than Arnold Schwarzenegger's biceps.
To end the evening, Channels of resistance (C4, 10.55pm) is the final
programme in a splendid documentary series examining the workings of
television.
</TEXT>
