<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 93 / Rises 'higher' in small companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SMALLEST and largest companies gave their managers and directors the
highest pay rises last year, research published today by the Institute of
Management shows.
Managers and directors of companies with a turnover of less than Pounds 25m
had an average 6.6 per cent increase in the 12 months to January. Other
institute studies have shown that those working in companies with a turnover
of Pounds 25m to Pounds 125m had average rise of 5.5 per cent last year.
Those in companies with a turnover of Pounds 125m-Pounds 600m received 5.1
per cent.
In the largest companies - above Pounds 600m - the trend reverses, with
managers getting increases averaging 7.2 per cent and directors 8.6 per
cent.
According to the latest study, in businesses with a turnover of less than
Pounds 25m the average manager now earns Pounds 27,504 and the average
director Pounds 50,803. The survey, covering nearly 2,500 people in 127
companies, was carried out by Remuneration Economics, the pay research
group.
Women directors fared significantly worse last year than their male
counterparts. Women's earnings increased by just 2.9 per cent, compared with
7 per cent for men. The gap between male and female managers' increases was
smaller - women had 6.4 per cent and men 6.5 per cent.
Large regional differences were highlighted by the survey. In central London
smaller businesses average pay for managers is Pounds 34,383 and for
directors Pounds 60,121. Managers in the south-west and Wales receive Pounds
22,270, and directors Pounds 43,435.
Mr Roger Young, the institute's director, said smaller companies were
catching up on pay after holding back for the past five years. 'The more
companies have delayered, the more responsibility has been taken by those
managers who have been left,' said Mr Young. Companies have had to give
above-average increases to remaining managers to 'build up morale', he
added.
The survey found the best-paid executives in smaller businesses worked in
computing, telecommunications and marketing. The worst-paid were in
production, distribution, personnel, and research and development.
April pay deals confirm the downward trend in settlement levels, according
to the research group Incomes Data Services. Three quarters of the increases
monitored in April were worth 1.5 per cent to 3.9 per cent. Pay had been
frozen in one case in 10.
The Smaller Business Review. Remuneration Economics, Survey House, 51
Portland Road, Kingston-upon-Thames, Surrey KT1 2SH. Pounds 180.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------
              ANNUAL PERCENTAGE INCREASE IN EARNINGS
 ----------------------------------------------------------------
COMPANY TURNOVER           MANAGERS      DIRECTORS       ALL
 ----------------------------------------------------------------
Under Pounds 25m             6.5            6.9          6.6
Pounds 25m-Pounds 125m       5.4            6.0          5.5
Pounds 125m-Pounds 600m      5.2            4.7          5.1
Pounds 600 and over          7.2            8.6          7.4
 ----------------------------------------------------------------
Source: Institute of Management
 ----------------------------------------------------------------
