<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 93 / Unions seek to block loss of Swan Hunter projects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL OFFICIALS of shipbuilding unions will be asked this week to back a
call for shipyard workers throughout the UK to refuse to work on three Type
23 frigates if they are moved from Tyneside shipbuilder Swan Hunter.
The motion was unanimously backed on Saturday at a Carlisle meeting of shop
stewards from all UK shipyards except Southampton-based Vosper Thornycroft.
Union leaders from Swan Hunter, which went into receivership 10 days ago
after a helicopter carrier order went to rival consortium VSEL/Kvaerner,
said the Vosper stewards had send a message supporting the motion.
Swan Hunter union officials expect the motion, proposed by Mr Jim McFall,
chairman of the shipyard negotiating committee of the Confederation of
Shipbuilding and Engineering Unions, to be endorsed by the committee when it
meets on Wednesday.
Mr Tommy Brennan, Tyne and Blyth CSEU chairman, said yesterday: 'If endorsed
it will be adopted as official policy of their unions.'
If the frigates are removed - a move Swans unions have pledged to prevent -
workers wherever they were sent would be balloted after union lawyers had
scrutinised the motion.
Some Swan Hunter workers, demoralised by uncertainty and poor alternative
job prospects, doubt they can count on solidarity from other yards.
Mr George Cook, a boilermaker, said as he left Swans on Friday: 'If it's
going to save their jobs, they'll work on them. It's a horrible situation,
it's look after number one. That's Tory Britain now.'
But Mr Brennan insisted: 'I'm sure the overwhelming majority won't touch
that job with a bargepole.'
Fitting out the frigates is vital to Swan's survival as a shipbuilder. It
would provide work until late 1994, giving the company the chance to bid for
other contracts and secure a buyer as a going concern.
The Ministry of Defence has given no undertaking that work can continue on
the frigates beyond this Friday.
