<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 93 / Manufacturing probe urged
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES SUCH as Swan Hunter and Leyland Daf are being allowed to collapse
while the government does nothing, Mr Roger Lyons, general secretary of the
MSF technical union, said yesterday.
Opening a debate on manufacturing at the union's annual conference in
Blackpool, Mr Lyons called for a royal commission to do the work that the
government had failed to do. He said: 'We are dealing with a long-term
problem that requires long-term solutions and a change in attitudes. We need
a new consensus in support of manufacturing industry.
'In addition to the campaigns we are waging now on behalf of our members, I
am writing to the prime minister and the leader of the opposition, Mr John
Smith, to propose the establishment of a royal commission on manufacturing.
'I know that royal commissions have their critics. I am therefore proposing
that this one operate in a radically different way. It would meet in public.
'It would take evidence in public. Its membership would be drawn from across
the political and industrial spectrum, including the trade union movement,
and it would be asked to report by the end of 1995 - just in time for a new
Labour government to consider its recommendations.'
