<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 93 / Industry's growth plans 'flawed'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANUFACTURING companies are forecasting a bright future for the next three
years but their growth plans are 'fundamentally flawed', says a study by
Pera International, one of Europe's leading business consultancies.
A Pera survey of 345 companies released this week - mainly in mechanical
engineering, medical engineering, and the electronics and automotive
industries - finds that 82 per cent expect business growth this year and 96
per cent predict significant growth within three years.
But nearly a quarter of respondents admitted they could not develop a growth
strategy, while nearly a third could not implement development plans.
In addition a fifth were unable to pinpoint their company's own strengths,
identify new business opportunities or recognise the factors critical to
their success.
The survey found that nearly 90 per cent of manufacturers had survived the
recession by cutting costs. This made them 'leaner' and more efficient but
had not increased or even protected their market share.
Pera says: 'Come the economic upturn, these companies will not be able to
capitalise on their own leanness.
'Many of their planned growth strategies cannot bear fruit, due to a lack of
specific skills to implement them. A lack of adequate financial resources is
also likely to scupper many hungry companies' plans for growth.'
It believes growth plans are flawed because of a worrying fundamental
inconsistency.
Manufacturers, understandably cautious, are mainly looking to develop within
their current core business. But if most organisations are adopting the same
develop-ment strategies only the 'outstanding few' will gain the increased
market share they expect, says Pera.
Most manufacturers surveyed also gave their employees, especially the sales
team, little credit for the company's success.
'This attitude contradicts respondents' desires to grow the business,' says
Pera. 'The traditional notion that 'the product sells itself' still
prevails.'
High Hopes, Poor Strategies: Can Industry Plan for Growth? Pera
International Management Centre, Lydiard Millicent, Swindon, Wiltshire, SN5
9LS.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
